    The stack trace confirms that the crash happens precisely at the statement  
    cur = cur->next; inside destroy_list. The program has already called        
    delete cur; on line 13, freeing the memory, and then immediately tries to   
    read from that memory in the increment step.                                
                                                                                
    --------------------------------------------------------------------------  
                                                                                
    Minimal local fix                                                           
                                                                                
    Change the body of destroy_list so that the next pointer is saved before    
    the current node is deleted:                                                
                                                                                
                                                                                
     static void destroy_list(Node *head) {                                     
         while (head) {                                                         
             Node *next = head->next;   // save next node                       
             delete head;               // free current node                    
             head = next;               // advance to saved next node           
         }                                                                      
     }                                                                          
                                                                                
                                                                                
    Why this works: next holds a valid pointer to the next node before the      
    delete, so the loop can safely advance without ever dereferencing freed     
    memory.                                                                     
                                                                                
    A one‑line alternative (still safe) is:                                     
                                                                                
                                                                                
     for (Node *cur = head; cur; cur = cur->next) {                             
         Node *tmp = cur;                                                       
         delete tmp;                                                            
     }                                                                          
                                                                                
                                                                                
    Here cur->next is accessed before the delete, eliminating the UAF.          
                                                                                
    --------------------------------------------------------------------------  
                                                                                
    More thorough root‑cause fix                                                
                                                                                
    While the minimal fix resolves the immediate crash, a robust design should  
    also address:                                                               
                                                                                
     1 Exception safety – if an exception is thrown while processing a node,    
       the rest of the list might remain allocated, leaking memory. Use a       
       std::unique_ptr or RAII wrapper to ensure deterministic cleanup.         
     2 Double‑free protection – ensure destroy_list is not called on a list     
       that has already been destroyed. A common pattern is to set the head     
       pointer to nullptr after destruction or to provide a separate            
       “is_destroyed” flag.                                                     
     3 Interface design – instead of raw Node*, expose a container (e.g., a     
       singly‑linked List class) that manages its own lifetime, providing       
       clear() that internally uses the safe deletion pattern. This isolates    
       the unsafe logic to a single well‑tested place.                          
     4 Testing with sanitizers – compile with -fsanitize=address,undefined and  
       run the program under Valgrind or ASan to catch similar UAF bugs         
       automatically.                                                           
                                                                                
    A more thorough rewrite might look like:                                    
                                                                                
                                                                                
     struct Node {                                                              
         int   value;                                                           
         Node *next;                                                            
         ~Node() = default;               // no special work needed             
     };                                                                         
                                                                                
     class LinkedList {                                                         
         Node *head_;                                                           
     public:                                                                    
         explicit LinkedList(Node *h = nullptr) : head_(h) {}                   
         ~LinkedList() { clear(); }                                             
                                                                                
         void clear() {                                                         
             while (head_) {                                                    
                 Node *next = head_->next;                                      
                 delete head_;                                                  
                 head_ = next;                                                  
             }                                                                  
         }                                                                      
                                                                                
         // non‑copyable, move‑able if desired                                  
         LinkedList(const LinkedList&) = delete;                                
         LinkedList& operator=(const LinkedList&) = delete;                     
         LinkedList(LinkedList&& other) noexcept :                              
     head_(std::exchange(other.head_, nullptr)) {}                              
         LinkedList& operator=(LinkedList&& other) noexcept {                   
             delete head_;                                                      
             head_ = std::exchange(other.head_, nullptr);                       
             return *this;                                                      
         }                                                                      
     };                                                                         
                                                                                
                                                                                
    With this wrapper, destroy_list can be replaced by simply calling           
    list.clear(); which internally uses the safe loop shown above.              
                                                                                
